        {
            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "I'm not entirely convinced this is something actionable without big workarounds.\nBy their nature, abbreviations require (neo)vim to have access to the (memory) buffer the cursor is currently writing in, so that it can look for _lhs_ and replace it with _rhs_. In terminal mode, however, neovim simply sends keycodes over to another running process.\n\nPersonally, I can imagine this feature being desired **only** when interacting with a shell prompt, in which case a native (of the shell) solution would be much more fitting.\n\nNB all I just said stems from three days of looking at the vterm source code in the neovim repo trying to get something out of this issue and no prior experience. Do  not trust blindly anything I say.",
