            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> By their nature, abbreviations require (neo)vim to have access to the (memory) buffer the cursor is currently writing in, so that it can look for _lhs_ and replace it with _rhs_. In terminal mode, however, neovim simply sends keycodes over to another running process.\n\nTrue. There is `:help prompt-buffer`. Also, it's planned to support full Nvim editing of shell prompts in a `:terminal`. Might require some hacks to yank (and later replace) the shell prompt input. However, neither of those cases would need terminal-mode mappings.",
